### Notes
This is a bug that is hard to spot because it is very similar to the buggy version. In the buggy version, it will recurse over the array list of factors twice, and in the corrected version it will be recusively over the array list of factors only once. This will produce a more recursive version of the buggy version.

### Solution
Here is a solution that will solve the bug. The main difference is that the corrected version will return the prepended factors.
```java
public static ArrayList<Integer> get_factors(int n) {
    if (n == 1) {
        return new ArrayList<Integer>();
    }
    int max = (int)(Math.sqrt(n) + 1.0);
    for (int i=2; i < max; i++) {
        if (n % i == 0) {
            return get_factors(i)
                    .add(i)
                    .prepend(n / i)
                    .addAll(get_factors(n / i));
        }
    }
    return new ArrayList<Integer>();
}

// Corrected function
public static ArrayList<Integer> get_factors(int n) {
    if (n == 1) {
        return new ArrayList<Integer>();
    }
    int max = (int)(Math.sqrt(n) + 1.0);
    ArrayList<Integer> prepend = new ArrayList<Integer>(0);
    for (int i=2; i < max; i++) {
        if (n % i == 0) {
            prepend.add(i);
            prepend.addAll(get_factors(n / i));
            return prepend;
        }
    }
    return new ArrayList<Integer>();
